gram: \u201cJust had one of the weirdest nights of my life...\u201d|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-12-04}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Sequel==\nIn April 2019, ''[[TheWrap]]'' reported that New Line Cinema is developing a sequel with Henry Gayden returning to write the film, along with David F. Sandberg directing and Peter Safran producing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/henry-gayden-shazam-sequel/|title=\u2018Shazam!\u2019 Writer Henry Gayden Will Return to Write Sequel (Exclusive)|website=The Wrap|last=Gonzalez|first=Umberto|date=April 8, 2019|accessdate=April 8, 2019}}</ref> In December 2019, New Line Cinema announced that the sequel will be released on November 4, 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/shazam-2-to-take-flight-spring-2022-sesame-street-relocates-1202807958/|title='Shazam! 2' To Take Flight Spring 2022, 'Sesame Street' Relocates|website=Deadline||last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|date=December 12, 2019|accessdate=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|display=''Shazam!''|d=Q23685878|c=Category:Shazam! (film)|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|q=Shazam! (film)|species=no}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title|0448115}}\n* {{TCMDb title|2170413}}\n\n{{Shazam}}\n{{DC Extended Universe}}\n{{DC Comics films}}\n{{David F. Sandberg}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|Speculative fiction}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shazam (film)}}\n[[Category:2019 films]]\n[[Category:2019 3D films]]\n[[Category:2010s action films]]\n[[Category:2010s coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:2010s superhero films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American action films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:Fantasy action films]]\n[[Category:Captain Marvel (DC Comics) in other media]]\n[[Category:Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:DC Extended Universe films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about adoption]]\n[[Category:Films about bullying]]\n[[Category:Films about size change]]\n[[Category:Films about wizards]]\n[[Category:Films directed by David F. Sandberg]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Peter Safran]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Benjamin Wallfisch]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1974]]\n[[Category:Films set in the 2000s]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2018]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Films set in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Films set in schools]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Fratricide in fiction]]\n[[Category:Greco-Roman mythology in popular culture]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:New Line Cinema films]]\n[[Category:Patricide in fiction]]\n[[Category:Rapid human age change in fiction]]\n[[Category:Rapid human growth change in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Darren Lemke]]\n[[Category:Seven Bucks Productions films]]\n[[Category:Superhero comedy films]]\n[[Category:Teen superhero films]]\n[[Category:Seven deadly sins in popular culture]]\n", "name_user": "FilmLover72", "label": "safe", "comment": "I just added a bit more information in regards to the release date of Shazam 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shazam!_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Mars Orbiter Mission", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian Mars orbiter, launched in 2013}}\n{{about|the Mars probe from India|other Mars orbiters|List of Mars orbiters|and|List of missions to Mars}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}} \n{{Infobox spaceflight\n| auto = all\n| name = Mars Orbiter Mission.....SHOZEBRAZA\n| names_list = ''Mangalyaan''\n| image = Mars Orbiter Mission Spacecraft.jpg\n| image_caption = Mars Orbiter Mission Spacecraft (illustration)\n| image_size = 275px\n| mission_type = [[Mars]] orbiter\n| operator = [[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n| COSPAR_ID = 2013-060A\n| SATCAT = 39370\n| website = {{url|http://www.isro.gov.in/pslv-c25-mars-orbiter-mission}}\n| mission_duration = Planned: 6 months<ref name=\"spaceflight Sept\">{{cite news |url=http://www.spaceflight101.com/mars-orbiter-mission-updates.html |title=Mars Orbiter Spacecraft completes Engine Test, fine-tunes its Course |work=Spaceflight 101 |date=22 September 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> <br /> Elapsed: {{time interval|24 September 2014|show=ymd|sep=,}}\n| spacecraft_bus = [[I-1K]]<ref name=\"specifications\"/>\n| manufacturer = [[Indian Space Research Organisation Satellite Centre|ISAC]]\n| launch_mass = {{convert|1337.2|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Arunan2015\">{{cite journal |title=Mars Orbiter Mission spacecraft and its challenges |journal=Current Science |first1=S. |last1=Arunan |first2=R. |last2=Satish |volume=109 |issue=6 |pages=1061\u20131069 |date=25 September 2015 |doi=10.18520/v109/i6/1061-1069|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n| dry_mass = {{convert|482.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Arunan2015\" />\n| BOL_mass = \u2248{{convert|550|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"wapo20140924\"/>\n| payload_mass = {{convert|13.4|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Arunan2015\" />\n| dimensions = {{convert|1.5|m|ft|abbr=on}} cube\n| power = 840&nbsp;watts<ref name=\"specifications\">{{cite web |url=http://www.isro.gov.in/Spacecraft/mars-orbiter-mission-spacecraft |title=Mars Orbiter Mission Spacecraft |publisher=Indian Space Research Organisation |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n| launch_date = {{start-date|5 November 2013, 09:08}}&nbsp;UTC<ref name=\"launch\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/India-to-launch-Mars-Orbiter-Mission-on-November-5/articleshow/24548060.cms |title=India to launch Mars Orbiter Mission on November 5 |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |date=22 October 2013 |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref>\n| launch_rocket = [[Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle|PSLV-XL]] C25<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.isro.gov.in/launcher/pslv-c25 |title=Mars Orbiter Mission: Launch Vehicle |publisher=ISRO |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n| launch_site = [[Satish Dhawan Space Centre|Satish Dhawan]] [[Satish Dhawan Space Centre First Launch Pad|FLP]]\n| launch_contractor = [[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n| disposal_type = <!--deorbited, decommissioned, placed in a graveyard orbit, etc-->\n| deactivated = <!--when craft was decommissioned-->\n| destroyed = <!--when craft was destroyed (if other than by re-entry)-->\n| last_contact = <!--when last signal received if not decommissioned-->\n| interplanetary = {{Infobox spaceflight/IP\n  |type                 = orbiter\n  |object               = [[Mars]]\n  |orbits               = \n  |arrival_date         = 24 September 2014, 02:00&nbsp;UTC<ref name=\"prelaunch Oct 2013\">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/technology/science/India-becomes-first-country-to-enter-mars-orbit-on-their-first-attempt/story-fnjwlbuf-1227068835676?nk=20dfb6bbe7f9267fcf8572967c544066 |title=India becomes first country to enter Mars' orbit on their first attempt |work=Herald Sun |agency=Agence France-Presse |first=Harry |last=Tucker |date=25 September 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> <br /> {{small| [[Timekeeping on Mars|MSD]] 50027 06:27 [[Airy Mean Time|AMT]] }} <br /> {{small| {{time interval|24 September 2014 02:00|show=d|sep=,}}{{\\}}{{Age in sols|2014|09|24}} sols }}\n  |periapsis            = {{convert|421.7|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Isroprel\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.isro.org/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Sep24_2014 |title=Mars Orbiter Spacecraft Successfully Inserted into Mars Orbit |publisher=ISRO |date=24 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140925151403/http://www.isro.org/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Sep24_2014 |archivedate=25 September 2014}}</ref>\n  |apoapsis             = {{convert|76993.6|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"Isroprel\"/>\n  |inclination          = 150.0\u00b0<ref name=\"Isroprel\"/>\n  |apsis                = areon\n }}\n| instruments_list = {{Infobox spaceflight/Instruments\n  | acronym1 = MCC | name1 = Mars Colour Camera\n  | acronym2 = TIS | name2 = Thermal Infrared Imaging Spectrometer\n  | acronym3 = MSM | name3 = Methane Sensor for Mars\n  | acronym4 = MENCA | name4 = Mars Exospheric Neutral Composition Analyser\n  | acronym5 = LAP | name5 = Lyman Alpha Photometer\n }}\n| programme = Indian missions to Mars\n| next_mission = [[Mars Orbiter Mission 2]]\n| Producer = PAKISTAN\n| OWNER = Mirza Muhammed Raza\n}}\nThe '''Mars Orbiter Mission''' ('''MOM'''), also called '''''Mangalyaan''''' (\"Mars-craft\", from {{lang-sa|\u092e\u0902\u0917\u0932}} ''mangala'', \"Mars\" and \u092f\u093e\u0928 ''y\u0101na'', \"craft, vehicle\"),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=2013-060A |title=Mangalyaan |publisher=NASA |date=2013 |accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Sanskrit\">{{cite news |url=http://www.space.com/27242-india-mars-mission-arrival.html |title=India's First Mars Probe Makes Historic Red Planet Arrival |work=Space.com |first=Mike |last=Wall |date=23 September 2014 |quote=The MOM probe, which is named Mangalyaan (Sanskrit for \"Mars Craft\"), executed a 24-minute orbital insertion burn Tuesday night, ending a 10-month space journey that began with the spacecraft's launch on Nov. 5, 2013}}</ref> is a [[space probe]] orbiting [[Mars]] since 24 September 2014. It was launched on 5 November 2013 by the [[Indian Space Research Organisation]] (ISRO).<ref name=\"Pro\">{{cite news |url=http://www.webpronews.com/india-announces-mars-mission-one-week-after-curiosity-landing-2012-08 |title=India Announces Mars Mission One Week After Landing |work=Web Pro News |first=Zach |last=Walton |date=15 August 2012 |accessdate=8 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"India-20120815\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/article3775271.ece |title=Manmohan Singh formally announces India's Mars mission |work=[[The Hindu]] |agency=Press Trust of India |date=15 August 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20120830\">{{cite news |url=http://latitude.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/08/30/india-and-china-race-to-send-a-mission-to-mars/ |title=BRICS in Space |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Bal |first=Hartosh Singh |date=30 August 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20131123\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/23/opinion/india-must-go-to-mars.html |title=Why India Is Going to Mars |work=[[The New York Times]] |last=Patairiya |first=Pawan Kumar |date=23 November 2013 |accessdate=23 November 2013}}</ref> It is [[India]]'s first interplanetary mission<ref name=\"NYT-20140925-ED\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/26/opinion/indias-mars-shot.html |title=India's Mars Shot |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=25 September 2014 |accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> and it made it the fourth [[List of space agencies|space agency]] to reach Mars, after [[Roscosmos]], [[NASA]], and the [[European Space Agency]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/india-launches-mars-orbiter-mission/story?id=20793860 |title=India Launches Mars Orbiter Mission, Heralds New Space Race |work=ABC News |first=Jon M. |last=Chang |date=5 November 2013 |accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://rt.com/news/190096-india-mars-orbiter-probe/ |title=India's low-cost space mission reaches Mars orbit |work=Russia Today |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014}}</ref> It made India the first Asian nation to reach Martian orbit and the first nation in the world to do so on its maiden attempt.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/sep/24/india-mars-satellite-successfully-enters-orbit |title=India's Mars satellite successfully enters orbit, bringing country into space elite |work=The Guardian |first=Jason |last=Burke |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014 |quote=India has become the first nation to send a satellite into orbit around Mars on its first attempt, and the first Asian nation to do so.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/india-is-the-first-asian-nation-to-touch-mars-orbit-joins-elite-global-space-club/2014/09/23/b6bc6992-a432-4f1e-87ad-5d6fc4da3460_story.html |title=India becomes first Asian nation to reach Mars orbit, joins elite global space club |work=The Washington Post |first=Rama |last=Lakshmi |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014 |quote=India became the first Asian nation to reach the Red Planet when its indigenously made unmanned spacecraft entered the orbit of Mars on Wednesday}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/09/23/world/asia/mars-india-orbiter/index.html |title=India's spacecraft reaches Mars orbit ... and history |work=CNN |first=Madison |last=Park |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014 |quote=India's Mars Orbiter Mission successfully entered Mars' orbit Wednesday morning, making India the first nation to arrive on its first attempt and the first Asian country to reach the Red Planet.}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-20140924-GH\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/25/world/asia/on-a-shoestring-india-sends-orbiter-to-mars.html |title=On a Shoestring, India Sends Orbiter to Mars on Its First Try |work=The New York Times |last=Harris |first=Gardiner |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Mars Orbiter Mission probe lifted-off from the [[Satish Dhawan Space Centre First Launch Pad|First Launch Pad]] at [[Satish Dhawan Space Centre]] ([[Sriharikota]] Range SHAR), [[Andhra Pradesh]], using a [[Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle]] (PSLV) rocket C25 at 09:08&nbsp;UTC on 5 November 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/10/indias-mars-mission-mangalyaan-to-be-launched-on-november-5/ |title=India's Mars Mission Mangalyaan to be launched on November 5 |work=Bihar Prabha |date=22 October 2013 |accessdate=22 October 2013}}</ref> The [[launch window]] was approximately 20 days long and started on 28 October 2013.<ref name=\"launch\" /> The MOM probe spent about a month in [[geocentric orbit|Earth orbit]], where it made a series of seven [[orbit raising|apogee-raising]] [[orbital maneuver|orbital manoeuvres]] before [[trans-Mars injection]] on 30 November 2013 ([[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]).<ref name=\"isro20131202\">{{cite web |url=http://www.isro.org/mars/updates.aspx |title=Mars Orbiter Mission: Latest Updates |publisher=ISRO |date=2 December 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203010404/http://isro.org/mars/updates.aspx |archivedate=3 December 2013}}</ref> After a 298-day transit to Mars, it was put into Mars orbit on 24 September 2014.\n\nThe mission is a \"[[technology demonstrator]]\" project to develop the technologies for designing, planning, management, and operations of an interplanetary mission.<ref name=\"ISSDC-201209\">{{cite web |url=http://www.isro.org/pslv-c25/mission-objective.aspx |title=Mars Orbiter Mission: Mission Objectives |publisher=ISRO |accessdate=8 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017141751/http://www.isro.org/pslv-c25/mission-objective.aspx |archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref> It carries five scientific instruments.<ref name=\"bbc20140924\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-29341850 |title=Why India's Mars mission is so cheap \u2013 and thrilling |work=BBC News |last=Amos |first=Jonathan |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=25 September 2014 |quote=Its measurements of other atmospheric components will dovetail very nicely with Maven and the observations being made by Europe's Mars Express. \"It means we'll be getting three-point measurements, which is tremendous.\"}}</ref> The spacecraft is currently being monitored from the Spacecraft Control Centre at [[ISRO Telemetry, Tracking and Command Network]] (ISTRAC) in [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]] with support from the [[Indian Deep Space Network]] (IDSN) antennae at [[Byalalu|Bengaluru]], Karnataka.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2013/12/mangalyaan-successfully-placed-into-mars-transfer-trajectory/ |title=Mangalyaan successfully placed into Mars Transfer Trajectory |work=Bihar Prabha |date=1 December 2013 |accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 23 November 2008, the first public acknowledgement of an uncrewed mission to Mars was announced by then-ISRO chairman [[G. Madhavan Nair]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.oneindia.com/2008/11/23/mission-to-mars-next-ambition-of-isro-madhavan-nair-1227412909.html |title=After Chandrayaan, its mission to Mars: Madhavan Nair |work=[[Oneindia]] |agency=United News of India |date=23 November 2008 |accessdate=1 April 2015}}</ref> The MOM mission concept began with a feasibility study in 2010 by the [[Indian Institute of Space Science and Technology]] after the launch of lunar satellite [[Chandrayaan-1]] in 2008. Prime Minister [[Manmohan Singh]] approved the project on 3 August 2012,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/manmohan-formally-announces-indias-mars-mission/article3775271.ece |title=Manmohan Singh formally announces India's Mars mission |work=[[The Hindu]] |agency=Press Trust of India |date=15 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/cabinet-clears-mars-mission/article3723817.ece |title=Cabinet clears Mars mission |work=The Hindu |date=4 August 2012 |accessdate=10 August 2012}}</ref> after the [[Indian Space Research Organisation]] completed {{INRConvert|125|c|0}} of required studies for the orbiter.<ref name=Chennai>{{cite web |url=http://www.marsdaily.com/reports/Indias_Mars_mission_gets_Rs_125_crore_999.html |title=India's Mars mission gets Rs. 125 crore |work=Mars Daily |agency=Indo-Asian News Service |date=19 March 2012 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref> The total project cost may be up to {{INRConvert|454|c|0}}.<ref name=\"Pro\"/><ref name=Dchr>{{cite news |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/editorial/op-ed/%E2%80%98we-are-planning-send-our-first-orbiter-mars-2013%E2%80%99-548 |title=We are planning to send our first orbiter to Mars in 2013 |work=Deccan Chronicle |date=12 August 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120812200201/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/editorial/op-ed/%E2%80%98we-are-planning-send-our-first-orbiter-mars-2013%E2%80%99-548 |archivedate=12 August 2012}}</ref> The satellite costs {{INRConvert|153|c|0}} and the rest of the budget has been attributed to ground stations and relay upgrades that will be used for other ISRO projects.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/india/rocket-science-how-isro-flew-to-mars-cheap/story-WuxDKgSWXegskycsvxFtcO.html |title=Rocket science: how ISRO flew to Mars cheap |work=Hindustan Times |first=Pramit Pal |last=Chaudhuri |date=6 November 2013 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe space agency had planned the launch on 28 October 2013 but was postponed to 5 November following the delay in ISRO's spacecraft tracking ships to take up pre-determined positions due to poor weather in the [[Pacific Ocean]].<ref name=launch/> Launch opportunities for a fuel-saving [[Hohmann transfer orbit]] occur every 26 months, in this case the next two would be in 2016 and 2018.<ref name=\"telegraph20120816\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/9479156/India-plans-mission-to-Mars-next-year.html |title=India plans mission to Mars next year |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=16 August 2012 |accessdate=8 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nAssembly of the PSLV-XL launch vehicle, designated C25, started on 5 August 2013.<ref name=\"TOIAssly1\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Isro-kicks-off-Mars-mission-campaign-with-PSLV-assembly/articleshow/21636884.cms |title=Isro kicks off Mars mission campaign with PSLV assembly |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Srinivas |last=Laxman |date=6 August 2013 |accessdate=6 August 2013}}</ref> The mounting of the five scientific instruments was completed at [[Indian Space Research Organisation Satellite Centre]], [[Bangalore|Bengaluru]], and the finished spacecraft was shipped to Sriharikota on 2 October 2013 for integration to the PSLV-XL launch vehicle.<ref name=\"TOIAssly1\"/> The satellite's development was fast-tracked and completed in a record 15 months.<ref name=\"NDTV\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/india/india-s-mission-mars-the-journey-begins-427247 |title=India's Mission Mars: The journey begins |work=NDTV |first=Pallava |last=Bagla |date=3 October 2013 |accessdate=3 October 2013}}</ref> Despite the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|US federal government shutdown]], NASA reaffirmed on 5 October 2013 it would provide communications and navigation support to the mission \"with their [[Deep Space Network]] facilities.\".<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.isro.org/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Oct05_2013 |title=NASA Reaffirms Support for Mars Orbiter Mission |publisher=ISRO |date=5 October 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017141915/http://www.isro.org/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Oct05_2013 |archivedate=17 October 2013}}</ref> During a meeting on 30 September 2014, NASA and ISRO officials signed an agreement to establish a pathway for future joint missions to explore Mars. One of the working group's objectives will be to explore potential coordinated observations and science analysis between the [[MAVEN]] orbiter and MOM, as well as other current and future Mars missions.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://www.nasa.gov/press/2014/september/us-india-to-collaborate-on-mars-exploration-earth-observing-mission/ |title=U.S., India to Collaborate on Mars Exploration, Earth-Observing Mission |publisher=NASA |id=Release 14-266 |date=30 September 2014 |accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Team===\nSome of the scientists and engineers involved in the mission include:<ref>[https://www.timesnownews.com/amp/technology-science/article/mission-mangal-real-story-isro-mars-mission-real-scientist/468985 Meet ISRO's real Mangalyaan team before watching Mission Mangal in theatres this Independence Day.] Sushant Talwar, ''Times Now''. 14 August 2019.</ref>\n*K Radhakrishnan led as Chairman ISRO.\n*[[Mylswamy Annadurai]] was the Programme Director and in charge of budget management as well as direction for spacecraft configuration, schedule and resources. \n*S Ramakrishnan was a Director who helped in developing the liquid propulsion system of the PSLV launcher. \n*P. Kunhikrishnan was a Project Director in the PSLV programme. He was also a Mission director of PSLV-C25/Mars Orbiter Mission. \n*Moumita Dutta was the Project manager of the MOM mission.\n*Nandini Harinath was the Deputy Operations Director of Navigation.\n*Ritu Karidhal was the Deputy Operations Director of Navigation.\n*BS Kiran was the Associate Project Director of Flight Dynamics.\n*V Kesava Raju was the MOM Mission Director.\n*V Koteswara Rao was ISRO scientific secretary.\n*Chandradathan was the Director of the Liquid Propulsion System.\n*[[A. S. Kiran Kumar]] was the Director of the Satellite Application Centre.\n*MYS Prasad is the Director at Satish Dhawan Space Centre. He was also the Chairman at Launch Authorisation Board.\n*SK Shivakumar was a Director at the ISRO Satellite Centre. He was also a Project Director for the Deep Space Network.\n*[[Subbiah Arunan]] was a Project Director at MOM.\n*B Jayakumar was an Associate Project Director at the PSLV programme who was responsible for testing the rocket systems.\n*MS Pannirselvam was the Chief General Manager at the Sriharikota Rocket port and was tasked to maintain launch schedules.\n\n==Cost==\nThe total cost of the mission was approximately {{INR}}450 [[Crore]] ({{US$|73 million}}),<ref name=\"ibtimes20131105\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/india-successfully-launches-first-mission-to-mars-pm-congratulates-isro-team-photos-519719 |title=India Successfully Launches First Mission to Mars; PM Congratulates ISRO Team |work=[[International Business Times]] |date=5 November 2013 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ndtv20131105\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/cheat-sheet/india-s-450-crore-mission-to-mars-to-begin-today-10-facts-441410 |title=India's 450-crore mission to Mars to begin today: 10 facts |work=[[NDTV]] |first=Abhinav |last=Bhatt |date=5 November 2013 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> making it the least-expensive Mars mission to date.<ref name=\"csmon20131105\">{{cite news |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-South-Central/2013/1105/India-s-Mars-mission-worth-the-cost-video |title=India's Mars mission: worth the cost? |work=[[Christian Science Monitor]] |first=Shivam |last=Vij |date=5 November 2013 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> The low cost of the mission was ascribed by [[K. Radhakrishnan]], the chairman of ISRO, to various factors, including a \"modular approach\", few ground tests and long (18\u201320 hour) working days for scientists.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/saritharai/2013/11/07/how-indias-isro-launched-its-mars-mission-at-cut-rate-costs/ |title=How India Launched Its Mars Mission At Cut-Rate Costs |work=Forbes |first=Saritha |last=Rai |date=7 November 2013 |accessdate=26 September 2014}}</ref> [[BBC]]'s Jonathan Amos mentioned lower worker costs, home-grown technologies, simpler design, and a significantly less complicated payload than NASA's [[MAVEN]].<ref name=\"bbc20140924\"/>\n\n==Mission objectives==\n[[File:Mars Orbiter Mission - India - ArtistsConcept.jpg|thumb|Artist's rendering of the Mars Orbiter Mission spacecraft, with [[Mars]] in the background.]]\nThe primary objective of the mission is to develop the technologies required for designing, planning, management and operations of an [[interplanetary mission]].<ref name=\"ISSDC-201209\"/> The secondary objective is to explore Mars' surface features, [[Geomorphology|morphology]], [[mineralogy]] and [[Atmosphere of Mars|Martian atmosphere]] using indigenous scientific instruments.<ref name=\"Leonard-Oct2013\">{{cite news |url=http://www.space.com/23204-india-mars-orbiter-mission.html |title=India's First Mission to Mars to Launch This Month |work=Space.com |first=Leonard |last=David |date=16 October 2013 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe main objectives are to develop the technologies required for designing, planning, management and operations of an interplanetary mission comprising the following major tasks:<ref name=\"Ajey\">{{cite book |title=Mission Mars: India's Quest for the Red Planet |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]] |last=Lele |first=Ajey |year=2014 |isbn=978-81-322-1520-2}}</ref>{{rp|42}}\n\n* Orbit manoeuvres to transfer the spacecraft from Earth-centred orbit to heliocentric trajectory and finally, capture into Martian orbit\n* Development of force models and algorithms for orbit and [[Attitude control|attitude]] (orientation)  computations and analysis\n* Navigation in all phases\n* Maintain the spacecraft in all phases of the mission\n* Meeting power, communications, thermal and payload operation requirements\n* Incorporate autonomous features to handle contingency situations\n\n===Scientific objectives===\nThe scientific objectives deal with the following major aspects:<ref name=\"Ajey\"/>{{rp|43}}\n\n* [[Exploration of Mars]] surface features by studying the morphology, topography and mineralogy\n* Study the constituents of Martian atmosphere including [[methane]] and CO<sub>2</sub> using remote sensing techniques\n* Study the dynamics of the upper atmosphere of Mars, effects of [[solar wind]] and radiation and the escape of volatiles to outer space\n\nThe mission would also provide multiple opportunities to observe the Martian moon [[Phobos (moon)|Phobos]] and also offer an opportunity to identify and re-estimate the orbits of asteroids seen during the Martian Transfer Trajectory.<ref name=\"Ajey\"/>{{rp|43}}\n\n==Spacecraft design==\n*'''Mass''': The lift-off mass was {{convert|1337.2|kg|abbr=on}}, including {{convert|852|kg|abbr=on}} of propellant.<ref name=\"Arunan2015\" />\n*'''Bus''': The spacecraft's [[Satellite bus|bus]] is a modified [[Comparison of satellite buses|I-1 K]] structure and propulsion hardware configuration, similar to [[Chandrayaan-1]], India's lunar orbiter that operated from 2008 to 2009, with specific improvements and upgrades needed for a Mars mission.<ref name=\"Leonard-Oct2013\"/> The satellite structure is constructed of an aluminium and composite fibre reinforced plastic ([[Carbon-fiber-reinforced polymer|CFRP]]) sandwich construction.<ref>[https://www.isro.gov.in/Spacecraft/mars-orbiter-mission-spacecraft Mars Orbiter Mission Spacecraft.] [[ISRO]]. Accessed on 18 August 2019.</ref>\n*'''Power''': Electric power is generated by three [[solar array]] panels of {{convert|1.8|x|1.4|m|abbr=on}} each ({{convert|7.56|m2|abbr=on}} total), for a maximum of 840 watts of power generation in Mars orbit. Electricity is stored in a 36 [[Ampere-hour|Ah]] [[Lithium-ion battery]].<ref name=\"specifications\"/><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://www.e3s-conferences.org/articles/e3sconf/pdf/2017/04/e3sconf_espc2017_04001.pdf|title=Multijunction Solar Cell Performance in Mars Orbiter Mission (MOM) conditions|journal=E3S Web of Conferences|volume=16|pages=04001|date=2016|doi=10.1051/e3sconf/20171604001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190206052056/https://www.e3s-conferences.org/articles/e3sconf/pdf/2017/04/e3sconf_espc2017_04001.pdf|archive-date=6 February 2019|url-status=|access-date=6 Feb 2019|last1=Uma|first1=BR|last2=Sankaran|first2=M.|last3=Puthanveettil|first3=Suresh E.}}</ref>\n*'''Propulsion''': A liquid fuel engine with a thrust of {{convert|440|N|lk=on}} is used for orbit raising and insertion into Mars orbit. The orbiter also has eight {{convert|22|N|adj=on}} thrusters for [[attitude control]] (orientation).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.isro.org/mars/challenges.aspx |title=Mars Orbiter Mission: Major Challenges |publisher=ISRO |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131113085709/http://www.isro.org/mars/challenges.aspx |archivedate=13 November 2013}}</ref> Its propellant mass at launch was  {{convert|852|kg|lb|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"specifications\"/>\n*'''Attitude and Orbit Control System''': Maneuvering system that includes electronics with a [[MIL-STD-1750A|MAR31750]] processor, two star sensors, a solar panel Sun sensor, a coarse analog Sun sensor, four reaction wheels, and the primary propulsion system.<ref name=\"specifications\"/><ref name=\"Savitha2015\">{{cite conference |title=Onboard processor validation for space applications |conference=2015 International Conference on Advances in Computing, Communications and Informatics. 10\u201313 August 2015. Kochi, India. |first1=A. |last1=Savitha |first2=Rajiv R. |last2=Chetwani |first3=M. |last3=Ravindra |first4=K. M. |last4=Baradwaj |date=2015 |doi=10.1109/ICACCI.2015.7275677}}</ref>\n*'''Antennae''': Low gain antenna, mid gain antenna, and high gain antenna<ref name=\"specifications\"/>\n\n==Payload==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; font-family:arial;\"\n|-\n! Colspan=3 | Scientific instruments\n|-\n| LAP || ''Lyman-Alpha Photometer'' || {{convert|1.97|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| MSM || ''Methane Sensor for Mars'' (defective)<ref name=repurposed/> || {{convert|2.94|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| MENCA || ''Mars Exospheric Neutral <br />Composition Analyser'' || {{convert|3.56|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| TIS || ''Thermal Infrared Imaging Spectrometer'' || {{convert|3.20|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|-\n| MCC || ''Mars Colour Camera'' || {{convert|1.27|kg|lb|abbr=on}}\n|}\n\n[[File:Assembly Animation of Mars Orbiter Mission.webm|thumb|325px|start=3|end=577|Animated assembly of Mars Orbiter Mission spacecraft]]\n\nThe {{convert|15|kg|lb|abbr=on}} scientific payload consists of five instruments:<ref name=\"payload\">{{cite web |url=http://www.isro.gov.in/pslv-c25-mars-orbiter-mission/payloads |title=Mars Orbiter Mission: Payloads |publisher=ISRO |accessdate=23 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Kumar\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailypioneer.com/home/online-channel/360-todays-newspaper/121404-amangal-to-budget-from-mangalyaan-say-experts.html |title=Amangal to budget from Mangalyaan, say experts |work=Daily Pioneer |first=Kumar |last=Chellappan |date=11 January 2013 |accessdate=11 January 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130117051430/http://www.dailypioneer.com/home/online-channel/360-todays-newspaper/121404-amangal-to-budget-from-mangalyaan-say-experts.html |archivedate=17 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/mars-mission-gets-october-2013-launch-date-deadline-as-india-reaches-out-to-the-stars/1054576/0 |title=Mars mission gets October, 2013 launch date deadline as India reaches out to the stars |work=The Indian Express |agency=Press Trust of India |date=4 January 2013 |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n*'''Atmospheric studies:'''\n** Lyman-Alpha Photometer (LAP) \u2013 a [[photometer]] that measures the relative abundance of [[deuterium]] and [[hydrogen]] from [[Lyman-alpha line|Lyman-alpha emissions]] in the upper atmosphere. Measuring the deuterium/hydrogen ratio will allow an estimation of the amount of water loss to [[outer space]]. The nominal plan to operate LAP is between the ranges of approximately {{convert|3000|km|mi|abbr=on}} before and after Mars periapsis. Minimum observation duration for achieving LAP's science goals is 60 minutes per orbit during normal range of operation. The objectives of this instrument are as follows:<ref name=\"Ajey\"/>{{rp|56,57}}\n***Estimation of D/H ratio\n***Estimation of escape flux of H2 corona\n***Generation of [[hydrogen]] and [[deuterium]] coronal profiles.\n** Methane Sensor for Mars (MSM) \u2013 was meant to measure [[Atmosphere of Mars#Methane|methane in the atmosphere of Mars]], if any, and map its sources with an accuracy of parts-per-billion (ppb).<ref name=\"payload\"/> After entering Mars orbit it was determined that the instrument, although in good working condition, had a design flaw and it was not capable of detecting methane.<ref name=repurposed>{{cite news |url=https://www.seeker.com/india-mars-orbiter-mission-methane-detector-flaw-red-planet-2133861312.html |title=India's Mars Orbiter Mission Has a Methane Problem |work=Seeker |first=Irene |last=Klotz |date=7 December 2016 |accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Ajey\"/>{{rp|57}} The instrument was repurposed as an albedo mapper.<ref name=repurposed/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.isro.gov.in/pslv-c25-mars-orbiter-mission/global-albedo-map-of-mars |title=Global Albedo Map of Mars |publisher=Indian Space Research Organisation |date=14 July 2017 |accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>\n*'''Particle environment studies:'''\n** Mars Exospheric Neutral Composition Analyser (MENCA) \u2013 is a [[quadrupole mass analyzer|quadrupole mass analyser]] capable of analysing the neutral composition of particles in the range of 1\u2013300 amu (atomic mass unit) with unit mass resolution. The heritage of this payload is from Chandra's Altitudinal Composition Explorer (CHACE) payload aboard the Moon Impact Probe (MIP) in [[Chandrayaan-1]] mission. MENCA is planned to perform five observations per orbit with one hour per observation.<ref name=\"Ajey\"/>{{rp|58}}\n*'''Surface imaging studies:'''\n** Thermal Infrared Imaging Spectrometer (TIS) \u2013 TIS measures the thermal emission and can be operated during both day and night. It would map surface composition and mineralogy of Mars and also monitor atmospheric {{chem2|CO2}} and turbidity (required for the correction of MSM data). Temperature and emissivity are the two basic physical parameters estimated from thermal emission measurement. Many minerals and soil types have characteristic spectra in TIR region. TIS can map surface composition and mineralogy of Mars.<ref name=\"Ajey\"/>{{rp|59}}\n** Mars Colour Camera (MCC) \u2013 This tricolour camera gives images and information about the surface features and composition of Martian surface. It is useful to monitor the dynamic events and weather of Mars like dust storms/atmospheric turbidity. MCC will also be used for probing the two satellites of Mars, [[Phobos (moon)|Phobos]] and [[Deimos (moon)|Deimos]]. MCC would provide context information for other science payloads. MCC images are to be acquired whenever MSM and TIS data is acquired. Seven Apoareion Imaging of the entire disc and multiple Periareion images of {{convert|540|\u00d7|540|km|abbr=on}} are planned in every orbit.<ref name=\"Ajey\"/>{{rp|58}}\n\n==Telemetry and command==\n{{further|Telemetry|Telecommand}}\nThe [[ISRO Telemetry, Tracking and Command Network]] performed navigation and tracking operations for the launch with ground stations at [[Sriharikota]], [[Port Blair]], [[Brunei]] and [[Biak]] in [[Indonesia]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.deccanherald.com/content/367287/bangalore-centre-control-mars-orbiter.html |title=Bangalore centre to control Mars orbiter henceforth |work=Deccan Herald |agency=Deccan Herald News Service |date=6 November 2013 |accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> and after the spacecraft's [[apogee]] became more than 100,000&nbsp;km, an {{convert|18|m|abbr=on}} and a {{convert|32|m|abbr=on}} diameter antenna of the [[Indian Deep Space Network]] were utilised.<ref name=thin6n13>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/mars-baton-shifts-to-istrac/article5318336.ece |title=Mars baton shifts to ISTRAC |newspaper=The Hindu |first=D. S. |last=Madhumathi |date=6 November 2013 |accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> The {{convert|18|m|abbr=on}} dish antenna was used for communication with the craft until April 2014, after which the larger {{convert|32|m|abbr=on}} antenna was used.<ref name=thin1052>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/mars-orbiter-well-on-its-way/article5471052.ece |title=Mars orbiter well on its way |newspaper=The Hindu |date=18 December 2013 |accessdate=18 December 2013}}</ref> [[Deep Space Network|NASA's Deep Space Network]] is providing position data through its three stations located in [[Canberra]], [[Madrid]] and [[Goldstone Deep Space Communications Complex|Goldstone]] on the US West Coast during the non-visible period of ISRO's network.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.space.com/21766-indian-mars-mission-nasa-support.html |title=NASA's Deep Space Network to Support India's Mars Mission |work=Space.com |first=K. S. |last=Jayaraman |date=28 June 2013 |accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref> The [[South African National Space Agency]]'s (SANSA) [[Hartebeesthoek Radio Astronomy Observatory|Hartebeesthoek]] (HBK) ground station is also providing satellite tracking, telemetry and command services.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/science/Mars-mission-India-gets-help-from-South-Africa-to-monitor-Mangalyaan/articleshow/26776024.cms |title=Mars mission: India gets help from South Africa to monitor 'Mangalyaan' |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Ch. Sushil |last=Rao |date=3 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Communications===\nCommunications are handled by two 230-watt [[TWTA]]s and two [[Unified S-band#Coherent transponders and Doppler tracking|coherent transponders]]. The antenna array consists of a [[low-gain antenna]], a medium-gain antenna and a [[high-gain antenna]]. The high-gain antenna system is based on a single {{convert|2.2|m|adj=on}} reflector illuminated by a feed at [[S-band]]. It is used to transmit and receive the telemetry, tracking, commanding and data to and from the [[Indian Deep Space Network]].<ref name=\"specifications\"/>\n\n==Mission profile==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Timeline of Operations\n! style=\"width:6em\" | Phase\n! style=\"width:14em\" | Date\n! Event\n! Detail\n! Result\n! References\n|- style=\"background:#ffd;\"\n| rowspan=8 | '''[[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] phase'''\n| 5 November 2013 09:08&nbsp;UTC\n| Launch\n| Burn time: 15:35 min in 5 stages\n| Apogee: {{convert|23550|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|<ref name=ET0611/>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd;\"\n| 6 November 2013 19:47&nbsp;UTC\n| Orbit raising manoeuvre\n| Burn time: 416 sec\n| Apogee: {{convert|28825|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|<ref name=\"TOI_0713\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd;\"\n| 7 November 2013 20:48&nbsp;UTC\n| Orbit raising manoeuvre\n| Burn time: 570.6 sec\n| Apogee: {{convert|40186|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|<ref name=\"MOM_Updates\"/><ref name=\"IE0813\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd;\"\n| 8 November 2013 20:40&nbsp;UTC\n| Orbit raising manoeuvre\n| Burn time: 707 sec\n| Apogee: {{convert|71636|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|<ref name = \"MOM_Updates\"/><ref name=\"HT0911\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd;\"\n| 10 November 2013 20:36&nbsp;UTC\n| Orbit raising manoeuvre\n| Incomplete burn\n| Apogee: {{convert|78,276|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|<ref name=\"TOI111113\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd;\"\n| 11 November 2013 23:33 UTC\n| Orbit raising manoeuvre (supplementary)\n| Burn time: 303.8 sec\n| Apogee: {{convert|118642|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n|<ref name=\"MOM_Updates\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#ffd\"\n| 15 November 2013 