dia |date=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ndtv.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/cheat-sheet/mangalyaans-next-successful-step-a-tricky-mid-course-correction-544123 |title=Mangalyaan's next successful step: a tricky mid-course correction |work=NDTV |first=Pallava |last=Bagla |editor-first=Shamik |editor-last=Ghosh |date=11 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"THin\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/mars-orbiter-gets-its-first-course-correction/article5446749.ece |title=Mars orbiter gets its first course correction |work=The Hindu |date=11 December 2013 |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#E6E6FA;\"\n| 11 December 2013 01:00 UTC\n| 1st Trajectory correction\n| Burn time: 40.5 sec\n| Success\n|<ref name=\"MOM_Updates\"/><ref name=\"zeenews.india.com\"/><ref name=\"ndtv.com\"/><ref name=\"THin\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#E6E6FA;\"\n| 9 April 2014\n| 2nd Trajectory correction (planned)\n| Not required\n| Rescheduled for 11 June 2014\n| <ref name=TPS-EL/><ref name=\"THin\"/><ref name=\"Recent_Status\">{{cite web |url=https://www.facebook.com/isromom/posts/1463309403906999 |title=ISRO's Mars Orbiter spacecraft has... |work=ISRO's Mars Orbiter Mission |publisher=Facebook.com |date=9 June 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Jun_TCM\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.isro.gov.in/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Apr09_2014 |title=Mars Orbiter Spacecraft Crosses Half Way Mark of its Journey |publisher=ISRO |date=9 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606045559/http://www.isro.gov.in/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Apr09_2014 |archivedate=6 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Tiruchirapalli/health-parameters-of-mars-orbiter-are-normal/article5742711.ece |title=Health parameters of Mars Orbiter are normal |work=The Hindu |first=S. |last=Ganesan |date=2 March 2014}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#E6E6FA;\"\n| 11 June 2014 11:00&nbsp;UTC\n| 2nd Trajectory correction\n| Burn time: 16 sec\n| Success\n| <ref name=\"Recent_Status\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-02/news/50272494_1_mars-orbit-insertion-mars-mission-mars-orbiter |title=Trajectory correction of Mars mission likely by June 11 |work=The Economic Times |agency=Press Trust of India |date=2 June 2014}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#E6E6FA;\"\n| August 2014\n| 3rd Trajectory correction (planned)\n| Not required<ref name=\"Recent_Status\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/specials/coverage/marsorbitermission/marsorbitermission/mangalyaan-on-track-no-path-correction-in-august/sp-article10-1247284.aspx |title=Mangalyaan on track, no path correction in August |work=Hindustan Times |first=Vanita |last=Srivastava |date=1 August 2014}}</ref>\n|\n|<ref name=TPS-EL/><ref name=\"THin\"/>\n|- style=\"background:#E6E6FA;\"\n| 22 September 2014\n| 3rd Trajectory correction\n|Burn time: 4 sec\n|Success\n|<ref name=TPS-EL/><ref name=\"THin\"/><ref name=\"TestFire\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.isro.org/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Sep22_2014 |title=Mars Orbiter Spacecraft's Main Liquid Engine Successfully Test Fired |publisher=ISRO |date=22 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924044216/http://www.isro.org/pressrelease/scripts/pressreleasein.aspx?Sep22_2014 |archivedate=24 September 2014}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#FAA\"\n| '''[[Areocentric orbit|Areocentric]] phase'''\n| 24 September 2014\n| Mars orbit insertion\n| Burn time: 1388.67 sec\n|Success\n| <ref name = \"Isroprel\"/>\n|}\n{{multiple image\n| align = left\n| direction = horizontal\n| width = 300\n| header = Animation of Mars Orbiter Mission\n| image1 = Animation of Mars Orbiter Mission trajectory around Earth.gif\n| caption1 = [[Geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] phase\n| image2 = Animation of Mars Orbiter Mission trajectory.gif\n| caption2 = [[Heliocentric orbit|Heliocentric]] phase\n| image3 = Animation of Mars Orbiter Mission trajectory around Mars.gif\n| caption3 = [[Areocentric orbit|Areocentric]] phase\n| footer = {{legend2|magenta|Mars Orbiter Mission}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|Lime|[[Mars]]}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|RoyalBlue|[[Earth]]}}{{\u00b7}}{{legend2|Yellow|[[Sun]]}} \n| total_width = \n| alt1 =\n}}\n{{clear}}\n\n===Launch===\n[[File:Mars Orbitor Mission Launch.jpg|thumb|left|Launch of the Mars Orbiter Mission]]\nISRO originally intended to launch MOM with its [[Geosynchronous Satellite Launch Vehicle]] (GSLV),<ref name=\"Lakdawalla Oct 30\">{{cite news |url =http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2013/10311230-india-prepares-to-take-flight-faq.html |title=India prepares to take flight to Mars with the Mars Orbiter Mission (MOM) |publisher=The Planetary Society |first=Emily |last=Lakdawalla |authorlink=Emily Lakdawalla |date=31 October 2013 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> but the GSLV failed twice in 2010 and still had issues with its [[cryogenic engine]].<ref>{{Cite web| url =https://www.planetary.org/blogs/jason-davis/20130729-india-prepares-to-return.html|title=India prepares to return troubled rocket to flight| website =www.planetary.org| access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> Waiting for the new batch of rockets would have delayed the MOM for at least three years,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/isros-mars-mission-why-mangalyaans-path-is-full-of-riders-215625.html |title=Isro's Mars Mission: Why Mangalyaan's path is full of riders |work=Tech2 |date=6 November 2013 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> so ISRO opted to switch to the less-powerful [[Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle]] (PSLV). Since it was not powerful enough to place MOM on a direct-to-Mars trajectory, the spacecraft was launched into a highly elliptical Earth orbit and used its own thrusters over multiple perigee burns (to take advantage of the [[Oberth effect]]) to place itself on a [[Trans-Mars injection|trans-Mars trajectory]].<ref name=\"Lakdawalla Oct 30\"/>\n\nOn 19 October 2013, ISRO chairman [[K. Radhakrishnan]] announced that the launch had to be postponed by a week for 5 November 2013 due to a delay of a crucial telemetry ship reaching [[Fiji]]. The launch was rescheduled <ref name=\"launch\"/> ISRO's PSLV-XL placed the satellite into Earth orbit at 09:50&nbsp;UTC on 5 November 2013,<ref name=Chennai/> with a perigee of {{convert|264.1|km|abbr=on}}, an apogee of {{convert|23903.6|km|abbr=on}}, and inclination of 19.20 degrees,<ref name=\"ET0611\">{{cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/news-by-industry/et-cetera/mars-mission-on-track-orbit-to-be-raised-on-thursday/articleshow/25317904.cms |title=Mars Mission on track; orbit to be raised on Thursday |work=The Economic Times |agency=Press Trust of India |date=6 November 2013}}</ref> with both the antenna and all three sections of the solar panel arrays deployed.<ref name=\"TOI0611\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Mars-mission-Scientists-start-raising-Mangalyaans-orbit/articleshow/25338759.cms |title=Mars mission: Scientists start raising Mangalyaan's orbit |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Arun |last=Ram |date=7 November 2013}}</ref> During the first three orbit raising operations, ISRO progressively tested the spacecraft systems.<ref name=\"TOI111113-1\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/science/Mars-mission-After-glitch-Isro-plans-supplementary-orbit-raising-operation-tomorrow/articleshow/25590366.cms |title=Mars mission: After glitch, Isro plans supplementary orbit-raising operation tomorrow |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Ch. Sushil |last=Rao |date=11 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe orbiter's dry mass is {{convert|475|kg|lb|abbr=on}} and it carried {{convert|852|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of fuel at launch.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.ursc.gov.in/interplanetary/html/mars.jsp|title=MARS Orbiter Mission|website=www.ursc.gov.in|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/indias-mars-mission-to-enter-mars-orbit-on-september-24/article6413143.ece|title=India to enter Mars orbit on September 24|last=Ians|date=2014-09-15|work=The Hindu|access-date=2019-11-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> Its main engine, a derivative of the system used on India's communications satellites, uses the bipropellant combination [[monomethylhydrazine]] and [[dinitrogen tetroxide]] to achieve the thrust necessary for [[escape velocity]] from Earth. It was also used to slow down the probe for Mars orbit insertion and, subsequently, for orbit corrections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/blog/isro-successfully-testfires-vital-engine-mars-orbiter-on-final-lap-46514|title=ISRO successfully test-fires vital engine; Mars orbiter on final lap|website=www.downtoearth.org.in|language=en|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref>\n\n'''Models used for MOM:'''<ref name=\"JPL_MDNAV\">{{cite web|url=http://issfd.org/2015/files/downloads/papers/001_Helfrich.pdf|title=A journey with MOM| date=|website=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190223212016/http://issfd.org/2015/files/downloads/papers/001_Helfrich.pdf|archivedate=23 February 2019|url-status=|accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| Planetary Ephemeris ||[[Jet Propulsion Laboratory Development Ephemeris|DE-424]]\n|-\n| Satellite Ephemeris|| MAR063\n|-\n| Gravity Model (Earth) || GGM02C (100x100)\n|-\n| Gravity Model (Moon) || GRAIL360b6a (20x20)\n|-\n| Gravity Model (Mars) || MRO95A (95x95)\n|-\n| Earth Atmosphere || ISRO: DTM 2012<br />JPL : DTM 2010\n|-\n| Mars Atmosphere || MarsGram 2005\n|-\n| DSN Station Plate Motion || ITRF1993 frame, plate motion epoch 01-Jan-2003 00:00 UTC\n|}\n\n===Orbit raising manoeuvres===\n[[File:Mars Orbiter Mission ISRO English.svg|thumb|Orbit trajectory diagram (not to scale)]]\nSeveral orbit raising operations were conducted from the [[Master Control Facility|Spacecraft Control Centre]] (SCC) at the [[ISRO Telemetry, Tracking and Command Network]] (ISTRAC) at Peenya, Bengaluru on 6, 7, 8, 10, 12 and 16 November by using the spacecraft's on-board propulsion system and a series of perigee burns. The first three of the five planned orbit raising manoeuvres were completed with nominal results, while the fourth was only partially successful. However, a subsequent supplementary manoeuvre raised the orbit to the intended altitude aimed for in the original fourth manoeuvre. A total of six burns were completed while the spacecraft remained in Earth orbit, with a seventh burn conducted on 30 November to insert MOM into a [[Heliocentric orbit|heliocentric]] [[Mars transfer orbit|orbit]] for its transit to Mars.{{citation_needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nThe first orbit-raising manoeuvre was performed on 6 November 2013 at 19:47&nbsp;UTC when the spacecraft's {{convert|440|N|adj=on}} [[Liquid-propellant rocket|liquid]] engine was fired for 416 seconds. With this engine firing, the spacecraft's [[apogee]] was raised to {{convert|28825|km|mi|abbr=on}}, with a [[perigee]] of {{convert|252|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"TOI_0713\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Isro-scientists-raise-orbit-of-Mars-spacecraft/articleshow/25368028.cms |title=Isro scientists raise orbit of Mars spacecraft |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Arun |last=Ram |date=7 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe second orbit raising manoeuvre was performed on 7 November 2013 at 20:48&nbsp;UTC, with a burn time of 570.6 seconds resulting in an apogee of {{convert|40186|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"MOM_Updates\">{{cite web |url=http://www.isro.org/mars/updates.aspx |title=Mars Orbiter Mission: Latest Updates |publisher=ISRO |date=8 November 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131108022139/http://www.isro.org/mars/updates.aspx |archivedate=8 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"IE0813\">{{cite news |url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/second-orbit-raising-manoeuvre-on-mars-mission-performed/1192410/ |title=Second orbit raising manoeuvre on Mars Mission performed |work=Indian Express |agency=Press Trust of India |date=8 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe third orbit raising manoeuvre was performed on 8 November 2013 at 20:40&nbsp;UTC, with a burn time of 707 seconds, resulting in an apogee of {{convert|71636|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name = \"MOM_Updates\"/><ref name=\"HT0911\">{{cite news |url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/space/isro-successfully-completes-third-orbit-raising-manoeuvre-of-mars-probe_888761.html |title=India's Mars probe performs third orbit raising manoeuvre |work=Zee News |agency=Zee Media Bureau |first=Philaso G. |last=Kaping |date=9 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth orbit raising manoeuvre, starting at 20:36&nbsp;UTC on 10 November 2013, imparted a [[delta-v]] of {{convert|35|m/s|abbr=on}} to the spacecraft instead of the planned {{convert|135|m/s|abbr=on}} as a result of underburn by the motor.<ref name=\"TOI111113\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/science/Mars-mission-faces-first-hurdle-4th-orbit-raising-operation-falls-short-of-target/articleshow/25584362.cms |title=Mars mission faces first hurdle, 4th orbit-raising operation falls short of target |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Ch. Sushil |last=Rao |date=11 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"TPS111013\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2013/11102001-a-hiccup-for-mars-orbiter-mission.html |title=A hiccup in the orbital maneuvers for Mars Orbiter Mission |publisher=The Planetary Society |first=Emily |last=Lakdawalla |authorlink=Emily Lakdawalla |date=10 November 2013}}</ref> Because of this, the apogee was boosted to {{convert|78276|km|mi|abbr=on}} instead of the planned {{convert|100000|km|mi|-3|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"TOI111113\"/> When testing the redundancies built-in for the propulsion system, the flow to the liquid engine stopped, with consequent reduction in incremental velocity. During the fourth orbit burn, the primary and redundant coils of the solenoid flow control valve of 440 newton liquid engine and logic for thrust augmentation by the attitude control thrusters were being tested. When both primary and redundant coils were energised together during the planned modes, the flow to the liquid engine stopped. Operating both the coils simultaneously is not possible for future operations, however they could be operated independently of each other, in sequence.<ref name=\"TOI111113-1\"/>\n\nAs a result of the fourth planned burn coming up short, an additional unscheduled burn was performed on 12 November 2013 that increased the apogee to {{convert|118642|km|mi|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"MOM_Updates\"/><ref name=\"TOI111113-1\"/> a slightly higher altitude than originally intended in the fourth manoeuvre.<ref name=\"MOM_Updates\"/><ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/science/Mars-mission-Isro-performs-last-orbit-raising-manoeuvre/articleshow/25862187.cms |title=Mars mission: Isro performs last orbit-raising manoeuvre |work=The Times of India |agency=Press Trust of India |date=16 November 2013 |accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> The apogee was raised to {{convert|192874|km|mi|abbr=on}} on 15 November 2013, 19:57&nbsp;UTC in the final orbit raising manoeuvre.<ref name=\"MOM_Updates\"/><ref name=\"timesofindia.indiatimes.com\"/>\n\n===Trans-Mars injection===\n{{further|Trans-Mars injection}}\n\nOn 30 November 2013 at 19:19&nbsp;UTC, a 23-minute engine firing initiated the [[Hohmann transfer orbit|transfer]] of MOM away from Earth orbit and on [[heliocentric orbit]] toward Mars.<ref name=\"isro20131202\"/> The probe travelled a distance of {{convert|780000000|km|mi}} to reach Mars.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://spaceflightnow.com/pslv/c25/131105launch/ |title=Indian spacecraft soars on historic journey to Mars |work=Spaceflight Now |first=Stephen |last=Clark |date=5 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Trajectory correction maneuvers ===\nFour trajectory corrections were originally planned, but only three were carried out.<ref name=TPS-EL/> The first trajectory correction manoeuvre (TCM) was carried out on 11 December 2013 at 01:00&nbsp;UTC by firing the {{convert|22|N|adj=on}} thrusters for a duration of 40.5 seconds.<ref name=\"MOM_Updates\"/> After this event, MOM was following the designed trajectory so closely that the trajectory correction manoeuvre planned in April 2014 was not required. The second trajectory correction manoeuvre was performed on 11 June 2014 at 11:00&nbsp;UTC by firing the spacecraft's 22 newton thrusters for 16 seconds.<ref name=update_june>{{cite news |url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2014-06-12/news/50536605_1_mars-orbiter-mission-mars-orbit-insertion-indian-deep-space-network |title=ISRO performs TCM-2 on Mars Orbiter Mission |work=The Economic Times |agency=Press Trust of India |date=12 June 2014 |accessdate=5 July 2014}}</ref> The third planned trajectory correction manoeuvre was postponed, due to the orbiter's trajectory closely matching the planned trajectory.<ref name=update_tcm_august>{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/specials/coverage/marsorbitermission/marsorbitermission/mangalyaan-on-track-no-path-correction-in-august/sp-article10-1247284.aspx |title=Mangalyaan on track, no path correction in August |work=Hindustan Times |first=Vanita |last=Srivastava |date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref> The third trajectory correction was also a deceleration test 3.9 seconds long on 22 September 2014.<ref name=\"TestFire\"/>\n\n===Mars orbit insertion===\n[[File:PM witnesses the insertion of Mars Orbiter Mission into Martian orbit.jpg|thumb|PM Narendra Modi witnesses the insertion of the spacecraft into Martian orbit]]\nThe plan was for an insertion into [[Areocentric orbit|Mars orbit]] on 24 September 2014,<ref name=\"prelaunch Oct 2013\"/><ref name=\"MOI\">{{cite web |url=http://www.isro.org/mars/pdf/press%20briefing%20on%20MOI.pdf |title=Mars Orbit Insertion |publisher=ISRO |first=V. Koteswara |last=Rao |date=15 September 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140924045734/http://www.isro.org/mars/pdf/press%20briefing%20on%20MOI.pdf |archivedate=24 September 2014}}</ref> approximately 2 days after the arrival of NASA's [[MAVEN]] orbiter.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.space.com/23204-india-mars-orbiter-mission.html |title=India's First Mission to Mars to Launch This Month |work=Space.com |first=Leonard |last=David |date=15 October 2013}}</ref> The 440-newton liquid apogee motor was test fired on 22 September at 09:00&nbsp;UTC for 3.968 seconds, about 41 hours before actual orbit insertion.<ref name=\"MOI\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/sci-tech/mars-orbiter-mission-isro-to-test-fire-engine-today_1473833.html |title=Mars Orbiter Mission: ISRO to test fire engine today |work=Zee News |agency=Zee Media Bureau |first=Ritu |last=Singh |date=22 September 2014 |accessdate=22 September 2014 |ref=zee9}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Mars-spacecraft-test-fired-successfully-to-enter-red-planets-orbit-on-Wednesday/articleshow/43150229.cms |title=Mars spacecraft test-fired successfully, to enter red planet's orbit on Wednesday |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Arun |last=Ram |date=22 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Date\n!Time (UTC)\n!Event\n|-\n| rowspan=1 | 23 September 2014\n|10:47:32\n|Satellite communication switched to medium gain antenna\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | 24 September 2014\n|01:26:32\n|Forward rotation started for deceleration burn\n|-\n|01:42:19\n|Eclipse started\n|-\n|01:44:32\n|[[Attitude control]] manoeuvre performed with thrusters\n|-\n|01:47:32\n|Liquid Apogee Motor starts firing\n|-\n|02:11:46\n|Liquid Apogee Motor stops firing\n|}\n\nAfter these events, the spacecraft performed a reverse manoeuvre to reorient from its deceleration burn and entered Martian orbit.<ref name=\"Isroprel\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.btvin.com/videos/watch/8916/india%E2%80%99s-maiden-mars-mission-makes-history |title=India's Maiden Mars Mission Makes History |publisher=Bloomberg TV India |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413203103/http://www.btvin.com/videos/watch/8916/india%E2%80%99s-maiden-mars-mission-makes-history |archive-date=13 April 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"wapo20140924\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/india-is-the-first-asian-nation-to-touch-mars-orbit-joins-elite-global-space-club/2014/09/23/b6bc6992-a432-4f1e-87ad-5d6fc4da3460_story.html |title=India becomes first Asian nation to reach Mars orbit, joins elite global space club |work=The Washington Post |first=Rama |last=Lakshmi |date=24 September 2014 |accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Status==\n[[File:The Chairman, ISRO, Shri A.S. Kiran Kumar releasing the Mars Atlas on the occasion of the completion of one year of Mars Orbiter Mission in Orbit, in Bangalore. The Scientific Secretary, ISRO, Dr. Y.V.N. Krishnamoorthy.jpg|thumb|The Chairman, ISRO, Shri A.S. Kiran Kumar releasing the Mars Atlas on the occasion of the completion of one year of Mars Orbiter Mission in Orbit, in Bengaluru. The Scientific Secretary, ISRO, Dr. Y.V.N. Krishnamoorthy]]\n\nThe orbit insertion put MOM in a highly elliptical orbit around Mars, as planned, with a period of 72 hours 51 minutes 51 seconds, a [[periapsis]] of {{convert|421.7|km|mi|abbr=on}} and [[apoapsis]] of {{convert|76993.6|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name = \"Isroprel\"/> At the end of the orbit insertion, MOM was left with {{convert|40|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} of fuel on board, more than the {{convert|20|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} necessary for a six-month mission.<ref name=\"momlife\">{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/science/Mars-Orbiter-Mission-looks-to-sniff-methane-on-comet/articleshow/43476830.cms |title=Mars Orbiter Mission looks to sniff methane on comet |year=2014 |work=The Times of India |pages= |accessdate=4 October 2014 |location=India}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 September 2014, MOM controllers published the spacecraft's first global view of Mars. The image was captured by the Mars Colour Camera (MCC).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2014/09290843-mars-orbiter-mission-delivers.html |title=Mars Orbiter Mission delivers on promise of global views of Mars |publisher=The Planetary Society |first=Emily |last=Lakdawalla |date=29 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 October 2014, the ISRO altered MOM's orbit so as to move it behind Mars for [[C/2013 A1|Comet Siding Spring's]] flyby of the planet on 19 October 2014. The spacecraft consumed {{convert|1.9|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} of fuel for the manoeuvre. As a result, MOM's apoapsis was reduced to {{convert|72000|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"planetary\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/guest-blogs/2014/1009-mars-orbiter-mission-shifts.html |title=Mars Orbiter Mission shifts orbit to take cover from Siding Spring |publisher=The Planetary Society |first=Srinivas |last=Laxman |date=9 October 2014}}</ref> After the comet passed by Mars, ISRO reported that MOM remained healthy.<ref name=\"hindu20141021\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/sci-tech/science/im-safe-and-sound-tweets-mom-after-comet-sighting/article6520803.ece |title=I'm safe and sound, tweets MOM after comet sighting |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=21 October 2014 |accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 2015, the ISRO reported that the MSM instrument was functioning normally and are studying Mars' [[albedo]], the reflectivity of the planet's surface. The Mars Colour Camera was also returning new images of the Martian surface.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Mars-Orbiter-Mission-sends-fresh-pictures-methane-sensors-are-working-fine/articleshow/46453692.cms |title=Mars Orbiter Mission sends fresh pictures, methane sensors are working fine |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Chethan |last=Kumar |date=26 September 2014 |accessdate=6 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/emily-lakdawalla/2015/03040850-mars-orbiter-mission-methane.html |title=Mars Orbiter Mission Methane Sensor for Mars is at work |publisher=The Planetary Society |first=Emily |last=Lakdawalla |date=4 March 2015 |accessdate=1 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March 2015, MOM completed its initial six-month mission in orbit around Mars. ISRO extended the mission by an additional six months; the spacecraft has {{convert|37|kg|lb|abbr=on}} of propellant remaining and all five of its scientific instruments are working properly.<ref name=\"extension 1\">{{cite news |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/mars-orbiter-mission-red-planet-nasa-maven/1/425499.html |title=Mars Orbiter Mission extended for another 6 months |work=India Today |agency=Indo-Asian News Service |date=24 March 2015 |accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The orbiter can reportedly continue orbiting Mars for several years with its remaining propellant.<ref name=\"indexpress20150415\">{{cite news |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/mangalyaan-can-survive-for-years-in-martian-orbit-isro-chief/ |title=Mangalyaan can survive for 'years' in Martian orbit: ISRO chief |work=The Indian Express |agency=Express News Service |date=15 April 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nA 17-day communications blackout occurred from 6 to 22 June 2015 while Mars' orbit took it behind the Sun from Earth's view.<ref name=\"Ajey\"/>{{rp|52}}\n\nOn 24 September 2015, ISRO released its \"Mars Atlas\", a 120-page scientific [[atlas]] containing images and data from the Mars Orbiter Mission's first year in orbit.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://zeenews.india.com/news/space/isro-releases-mars-atlas-to-mark-mangalyaans-first-birthday-in-space_1801594.html |title=ISRO releases Mars atlas to mark Mangalyaan's first birthday in space |work=Zee News |agency=Zee Media Bureau |date=24 September 2015 |accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the first science results of the mission were published in ''[[Geophysical Research Letters]]'', presenting measurements obtained by the spacecraft's MENCA instrument of the [[Atmosphere of Mars|Martian exosphere]].<ref name=\"planetary20160302\">{{cite web |url=http://www.planetary.org/blogs/guest-blogs/2016/0225-menca-brings-divine-wealth.html |title=MENCA brings divine wealth from Mars: First science results from the Mars Orbiter Mission |publisher=The Planetary Society |first=Syed Maqbool |last=Ahmed |date=2 March 2016 |accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Bhardwaj2016\">{{cite journal |title=On the evening time exosphere of Mars: Result from MENCA aboard Mars Orbiter Mission |journal=[[Geophysical Research Letters]] |first1=Anil |last1=Bhardwaj |first2=Smitha V. |last2=Thampi |first3=Tirtha Pratim |last3=Das |first4=M. B. |last4=Dhanya |first5=Neha |last5=Naik |first6=Dinakar Prasad |last6=Vajja |first7=P. |last7=Pradeepkumar |first8=P. |last8=Sreelatha |first9=G. |last9=Supriya |first10=Abhishek J. |last10=K. |first11=S. V. |last11=Mohankumar |first12=R. Satheesh |last12=Thampi |first13=Vipin K. |last13=Yadav |first14=B. |last14=Sundar |first15=Amarnath |last15=Nandi |first16=G. Padma |last16=Padmanabhan |first17=A. V. |last17=Aliyas |display-authors=5 |volume=43 |issue=5 |pages=1862\u20131867 |date=March 2016 |doi=10.1002/2016GL067707 |bibcode=2016GeoRL..43.1862B|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nDuring 18 to 30 May 2016, a communication whiteout occurred with Earth coming directly between Sun and Mars. Due to high solar radiation, sending commands to spacecraft was avoided and payload operations were suspended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isro.gov.in/mom-successfully-came-out-of-%E2%80%98whiteout%E2%80%99-phase|title=MOM successfully came out of 'whiteout' Phase - ISRO|website=www.isro.gov.in|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 January 2017, MOM's orbit was altered to avoid the impending eclipse season. With a burn of eight 22&nbsp;N thrusters for 431 seconds, resulting in a velocity difference of {{convert|97.5|m/s|km/h}} using {{convert|20|kg|lb}} of propellant (leaving 13&nbsp;kg remaining), eclipses were avoided until September 2017. The battery is able to handle eclipses of up to 100 minutes.<ref name=\"2017-01-24_SD\">{{cite news |url=http://www.marsdaily.com/reports/Long_Eclipse_Avoidance_Manoeuvres_Performed_Successfully_on_MOM_Spacecraft_999.html |title=Long Eclipse Avoidance Manoeuvres Performed Successfully on MOM Spacecraft |work=Mars Daily |date=24 January 2017 |accessdate=24 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 May 2017, MOM reached 1,000 days (973 [[Timekeeping on Mars#Sols|sols]]) in orbit around Mars. In that time, the spacecraft completed 388 orbits of the planet and relayed more than 715 images back to Earth. ISRO officials stated that it remains in good health.<ref name=\"hindustan20170619\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/health/india-s-mars-orbiter-completes-1000-days-in-orbit-and-is-still-going-strong/story-fcswttvZZDtSq7BDzei3qI.html |title=India's Mars Orbiter completes 1000 days in orbit and is still going strong |work=Hindustan Times |first=Malavika |last=Vyawahare |date=19 June 2017 |accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 September 2018, MOM completed 4 years in its orbit around Mars, although the designed mission life was only six months. Over these years, MOM's Mars Colour Camera has captured over 980 images that were released to the public. The probe is still in good health and continues to work nominally.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.isro.gov.in/update/24-sep-2018/mars-orbiter-mission-mom-completes-4-years-its-orbit |title=Mars Orbiter Mission (MOM) completes 4 years in its orbit |publisher=Indian Space Research Organisation |date=24 September 2018 |access-date=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 September 2019, MOM completed 5 years in orbit around Mars, sending 2 terabytes of imaging data, and had enough propellant to complete another year in orbit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/science/isros-mars-mission-mangalyaan-completes-5-years-was-meant-to-last-only-6-months-2106873|title=ISRO's Mars Mission Completes 5 Years, Was Meant To Last Only 6 Months|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" heights=\"140px\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:One of the first images of the surface of Mars taken by the Mangalyaan on September 25, 2014.jpg|One of the first images of the surface of Mars taken by MOM on 25 September 2014\nFile:Arsia Mons - Mars Orbiter Mission (30108068296).png|Mangalyaan's image of Arsia Mons\nFile:Tharsis and Valles Marineris - Mars Orbiter Mission (30055660701).png|Image of Tharsis and Valles Marineris by Mangalyaan\nFile:Mars as seen from Mangalyaan (MOM).png|Mars as seen from Mangalyaan\nFile:Syrtis Major - Mars Orbiter Mission (29512601624).png|Three frame Mars Orbiter Mission Mars Color Camera mosaic of the Syrtis Major region on 24 September 2015.\nFile:NorthMars.jpg|North Pole\n</gallery>\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:2000 rupee back.jpg|thumb|right|Illustration of Mars Orbiter Mission spacecraft on \u20b9 2,000 currency bill]]\nIn 2014, China referred to India's successful Mars Orbiter Mission as the \"Pride of Asia\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ibtimes.co.uk/china-heralds-indias-mars-mission-mangalyaan-pride-asia-1466953 |title=China Heralds India's Mars Mission Mangalyaan as 'Pride of Asia' |work=[[International Business Times]] |last=Sridharan |first=Vasudevan |date=24 September 2014 |access-date=25 March 2018}}</ref> The Mars Orbiter Mission team won US-based [[National Space Society]]'s 2015 [[Space Pioneer Awards|Space Pioneer Award]] in the science and engineering category. NSS said the award was given as the Indian agency successfully executed a Mars mission in its first attempt; and the spacecraft is in an elliptical orbit with a high apoapsis where, with its high resolution camera, it is taking full-disk colour imagery of Mars. Very few full disk images have ever been taken in the past, mostly on approach to the planet, as most imaging is done looking straight down in mapping mode. These images will aid planetary scientists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.nss.org/?p=4622 |title=Indian Space Research Organization Mars Orbiter Programme Team Wins National Space Society's Space Pioneer Award for Science and Engineering |publisher=National Space Society |first=David |last=Brandt-Erichsen |date=12 January 2015 |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/isro-mars-orbiter-mission-team-wins-space-pioneer-award-726885 |title=ISRO Mars Orbiter Mission Team Wins Space Pioneer Award |work=NDTV |agency=Press Trust of India |date=14 January 2015 |accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.isro.gov.in/2015-space-pioneer-award-was-presented-to-isro-mars-orbiter-mission |title=2015 Space Pioneer Award was presented to ISRO for Mars Orbiter Mission |work=ISRO |date=20 May 2015 |accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nAn illustration of the Mars Orbiter Mission spacecraft is featured on the reverse of the [[Indian 2000-rupee note|{{INR|2,000}} currency note]] of India.<ref name=\"Firstpost 2016\">{{cite news |url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/rs-500-and-rs-1000-banned-new-rs-2000-currency-note-to-feature-mangalyaan-raised-bleed-lines-3095624.html |title=Rs 500 and Rs 1,000 banned: New Rs 2,000 currency note to feature Mangalyaan, raised bleed lines |work=[[Firstpost]] |date=8 November 2016 |accessdate=12 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nAn image taken by the Mars Orbiter Mission spacecraft was the cover photo of the November 2016 issue of ''[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]]'' magazine, for their story \"Mars: Race to the Red Planet\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2017/02/india-eyes-return-mars-and-first-run-venus |title=India eyes a return to Mars and a first run at Venus |work=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |first=Pallava |last=Bagla |date=17 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://press.nationalgeographic.com/2016/10/10/national-geographic-magazine-november-2016/ |title=''National Geographic'' (cover) |magazine=[[National Geographic]] |date=November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Follow-up mission==\nISRO plans to develop and launch a follow-up mission called [[Mars Orbiter Mission 2]] (MOM-2 or ''Mangalyaan-2'') with a greater scientific payload to Mars in 2024.<ref name=\"RS_20190718\">{{Cite web|url=https://pqars.nic.in/annex/249/Au2955.pdf|title=Rajya Sabha Unstarred Question No. 2955|last=Jatiya|first=Satyanarayan|date=18 July 2019|website=|archive-url=https://imgur.com/a/SXXyGzC|archive-date=30 August 2019|url-status=live|access-date=30 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://cospar2018.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/COSPAR-2018-Abstract-Book_July21-2018-UPDATE.pdf |title=COSPAR 2018: Scientific Assembly Abstracts |website=Cospar2018.org |date=21 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"tecake20160128\">{{cite news |url=http://tecake.in/news/space/india-join-hands-france-next-mars-mission-scheduled-2020-16964.html |title=India's French Connection: CNES and ISRO jointly will develop Mangalyaan 2 |work=The TeCake |first=Kanishk |last=Singh |date=28 January 2016 |accessdate=29 March 2016}}</ref> The orbiter will use [[aerobraking]] to reduce [[apoapsis]] of its initial orbit and reach an altitude more suitable for scientific observation.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/With-82-launches-in-a-go-Isro-to-rocket-into-record-books/articleshow/55123860.cms |title=With 82 launches in a go, Isro to rocket into record books |work=The Times of India |agency=Times News Network |first=Srinivas |last=Laxman |date=29 October 2016 |access-date=3 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The 2019 Hindi film ''[[Mission Mangal]]'' is loosely based on India's mission to Mars.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n*A web series called ''[[Mission Over Mars]]'' is loosely based on India's Mars mission.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Solar System|Spaceflight|India}}\n\n* {{annotated link|Department of Space}}\n* {{annotated link|ExoMars Trace Gas Orbiter}}\n* [[List of ISRO missions]]\n* [[List of Mars orbiters]]\n* [[List of missions to Mars]]\n* {{annotated link|Mars Express}}\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mars Orbiter Mission}}\n* [http://www.isro.gov.in/pslv-c25-mars-orbiter-mission Mars Orbiter Mission website]\n* [http://www.isro.gov.in/sites/default/files/pdf/pslv-brochures/pslv-c25-brochure.pdf Mars Orbiter Mission brochure]\n\n{{Mars spacecraft}}\n{{Indian space programme}}\n{{Indian spacecraft}}\n{{PSLV}}\n{{Solar System probes}}\n{{Orbital launches in 2013}}\n{{2013 in space}}\n{{2014 in space}}\n\n[[Category:ISRO space probes]]\n[[Category:Missions to Mars]]\n[[Category:Space probes launched in 2013]]\n[[Category:2013 in India]]\n[[Category:Artificial satellites orbiting Mars]]\n[[Category:Geography of Mars]]\n[[Category:Spacecraft launched by PSLV rockets]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian Mars orbiter, launched in 2013}}\n{{about|the Mars probe from India|other Mars orbiters|List of Mars orbiters|and|List of missions to Mars}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}} \n{{Infobox spaceflight |auto=all\n| name                  = Mars Orbiter Mission\n| names_list            = ''Mangalyaan''\n\n| image                 = Mars Orbiter Mission Spacecraft.jpg\n| image_caption         = Mars Orbiter Mission Spacecraft (illustration)\n| image_size            = 275px\n\n| mission_type          = [[Mars]] orbiter\n| operator              = [[Indian Space Research Organisation|ISRO]]\n| COSPAR_ID             = 2013-060A\n| SATCAT                = 39370\n| website               = {{url|http://www.i